## Pod Limit Management

Docker Desktop's single-node K8s cluster defaults to **110 pods maximum**.

### Check current usage
```bash
kubectl get nodes -o jsonpath='{.items[0].status.allocatable.pods}'  # max
kubectl get pods --all-namespaces --no-headers | wc -l               # current
```

### When nearing the limit (>100 pods)
```bash
# Identify placeholder deployments using traefik/whoami or nginx:latest
kubectl get deployments --all-namespaces \
  -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.namespace}{"\t"}{.metadata.name}{"\t"}{.spec.template.spec.containers[0].image}{"\n"}{end}' \
  | grep -E "whoami|placeholder|nginx:latest"

# Delete them manually to free pod slots
kubectl delete deployment <name> -n <namespace>
```

**NEVER delete tier 1-2 pods (medinovai-registry, medinovai-data-services, etc.) to free capacity.**
Only remove old placeholder test deployments.

### Prevent hitting the limit
- Deploy stubs with `replicas: 1` (the engine default)
- Remove completed/failed Jobs: `kubectl delete jobs --field-selector=status.successful=1 -A`
- Keep `Evicted` pods cleaned: `kubectl get pods -A | grep Evicted | awk '{print $1,$2}' | xargs -n2 kubectl delete pod -n`
